<Layout title="Hoppscotch: Lightweight API Testing — Rupadana">
  <article class="reveal">
    <span class="tag">API</span>
    <h1>Hoppscotch: The Lightweight, Open Source Postman Alternative</h1>
    <div class="meta">A fast, web-native, and open-source API development suite designed for modern workflows.</div>

    <div class="card article-content">
      <p>
        Every backend developer needs a reliable tool to test their endpoints. For years, <strong>Postman</strong> was the undisputed king. But over time, many developers—myself included—have noticed it becoming increasingly "bloated," requiring accounts for basic features and consuming significant system resources.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        This is where <strong>Hoppscotch</strong> (formerly known as Postwoman) shines. It is a lightweight, web-first alternative that brings back the simplicity of API testing.
      </p>

      <h2>What makes Hoppscotch different?</h2>
      <p>
        The most striking difference is the philosophy. Hoppscotch was built to be fast and accessible. Because it’s web-native, you don’t even need to install a desktop app; you can just open a browser tab and start testing immediately.
      </p>

      <h3>Key Features:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Multi-Protocol Support:</strong> It handles REST, GraphQL, WebSockets, Socket.io, MQTT, and even gRPC.</li>
        <li><strong>Zero Friction:</strong> No mandatory sign-ups. You can start making requests the second the page loads.</li>
        <li><strong>Open Source:</strong> You can inspect the code, contribute, or even self-host it on your own VPS using Docker.</li>
        <li><strong>Minimalist UI:</strong> A clean, focused interface that puts your API requests and responses front and center without unnecessary distractions.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Pro Tip:</strong> If you are running on a server with limited RAM (like a small VPS), Hoppscotch is much easier on your resources than traditional Electron-based desktop clients.
      </div>

      <h2>Privacy and Self-Hosting</h2>
      <p>
        In an era where data privacy is paramount, Hoppscotch offers a significant advantage. Since it is open source, you can deploy your own instance of Hoppscotch. This ensures that your sensitive API keys and internal endpoints never leave your own infrastructure.
      </p>

      <p>
        For teams, it offers excellent collaboration features like shared collections and environment variables, allowing you to sync your testing setup across your entire engineering organization without relying on a third-party cloud provider.
      </p>

      <h2>Why should you switch?</h2>
      <p>
        If you find yourself waiting for your current API client to load, or if you're tired of being nagged to create an account just to send a simple <code>GET</code> request, Hoppscotch is for you. It honors the "tools should stay out of your way" philosophy that we value in modern development.
      </p>

      <h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
      <p>
        Hoppscotch isn't just a "clone" of Postman; it's a faster, more open evolution of what an API development suite should be. Whether you're building a simple blog backend or a complex microservice architecture, it's worth adding to your toolkit.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        Ready to try it out? Head over to <a class="inline-link" href="https://hoppscotch.io" target="_blank">hoppscotch.io</a> or check out their <a class="inline-link" href="https://github.com/hoppscotch/hoppscotch" target="_blank">GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

